While virtually all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
It does not prevent sufficient reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to place the new album of Maxim Turbonc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, just like a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time supporting listeners purchased for twenty crowns in the market.
These are two extremes, among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The life of batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than simply reading music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the first functions, phone calls and SMS sending, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
