If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if you are going to listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading MP3.
Practically all the furniture is now capable of it.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to music formats that mobile or player is able to read.
All come to read the MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you right this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also read WMA music.
The AAC (format used by the Apple firm and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Simply visit the corresponding operator's (or other supplier's) web pages from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason to obtain a musical mobile.
The operators' offer is unfortunately miserable and, in most cases, it is limited to fast-made tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet or even the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their mobile on their own.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have listeners or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in enclosures, which have virtually all the mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical furniture is their price.
The least expensive normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand crowns, we can have a walkman already very suitable.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the absence of exit for ordinary listeners.
