A first virtual operator will win Czechia this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for long.
We have already mentioned, many times, on Mobil.cz, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTú (The Czech Telecommunications Office), who reported that the price of an SMS was higher at home than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the recent steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of cheaper Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czechia remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that goes far beyond 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), who declared several times that there was no room in Chechnya for another operator, made chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network seems to have no more chance (in fact, now he would find only hard frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable decrease in prices, to which classical operators should then also react.
Yet, even before the entry of the riots such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today at home would be heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to earn over 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
Let us add that behind Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which has among other things the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, free from relatively high construction, operation and maintenance costs of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators look like low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as expensive in Britain as its competitors.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity.
Indeed, this operator specifically aims at men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is hard to say, if such a concept would be likely to work with us too.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone's spokesperson, doubting: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czechia, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but in Chechnya negotiations are not very supportive.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone entertainment for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that Czech operators were not in any case in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, does not hide, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services but also mobile.
And the sooner it's gonna be the best.
We have already held negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have been able to move forward in the negotiations," said the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to informal information, it seems that we could perhaps welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"At the moment, we do not think there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
At the moment, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vladimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobilea Kemrová's spokesperson states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the fulfilment of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický said in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and above all in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
Mobile operators' approach is easily understandable, another operator's entry would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
So, what good is it to facilitate the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to feel like a larron in the fair. The Chicane accompanying the creation of the U:phone also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTU, at the creation of the U:fon, was the one exercised by T-Mobile.
This shows information that is accessible to the public from the ČTú web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon lends itself as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this connection: "The competition on the mobile market has been, moreover, recently enlarged by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of mobile operators here, the indifference of Czech regulators seems to be disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of Čtú, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in the economic competition in Czechia.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts, in response to this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the time being, since the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa in response to our question from the UOHS external relations department.
A declaration thus made would not surprise operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and also care, so that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than misleading.
Even more so than Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure in the sense of honest market operation and a lower price does not appear to be part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a chance, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is likely to be due to random and hard competition.
"The Office has not identified signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none of them have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTU, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator quite logically has the monopoly on his network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators are performing in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned), show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
To resume responsibility for the ČTU is a fairly common tour of communications, through which the UOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of ČTú's powers in the field of competition in telecommunications, although many specialists were promising to improve the situation.
However, the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
That said, the operation of some sort of virtual pseudo-operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unclear.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
In most cases, companies dealing with multi-level marketing are involved.
Specialized mobile telephone services are provided, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are generally only available to elected officials.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important client, she gets special price offers (and others).
What is a problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you think happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could result in a cessation of cooperation with the society in question," replied our question regarding this Martina Kemrová problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not been achieved until those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of clients.
However, no operator can take a decision against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to actual virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card on their phones is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
This is precisely what should seem strange to Čtú.
In addition, another question is asked to the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the operators' explanations, which claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbidding it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has resulted in a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, virtually in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, which were defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue as a hot potato that is being disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in the skills is more profitable to them.
But don't throw the sleeve after the cognane.
If the flow information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will be unable to remain impassable in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of others concerned.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
