The Sudets called for a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the South asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated in the United States.
This is the result of a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (Scientific Library of the Bohème du Sud).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Germans of the Sudetes allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This derives from, among other things, a preserved letter in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter ask the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of the Bohemian region) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation very well and we want to be sure that the words proclaim that American troops come into German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "People, whose fate of Šumava stands out."
Given that the rally in Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, reckless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has not at all contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the fourth million inhabitants," the letter says.
The alleged reason the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech Oppressors".
If the President of the USA doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of the history of the post-war war, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudets of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least find out that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them had such an opportunity.
Some were expecting the United States and Great Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the South.
Others thought they'd just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, it was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
At the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war thought that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the Republic.
