Rats also have sensations
A rat or a safe escape in the face of danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he has the same experience when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else so far could prove it just as one cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains present the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult terrains because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, escape or attack.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduct a comparable subjective life.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our life subjective to that of the animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and management and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
All the less, therefore, for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant particularity could reside in the linguistic nature of the Man: a large part of his existence being related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was not to depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is so difficult to determine what awareness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, as a result of this particular Hardware, to analyze on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses major problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious life, but there is another aspect of the consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal awareness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and that is exactly what happened in short-term memory studies of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
