"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no strange clothes.
The essence of the flamenco masters, released from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen views of artists who do not care to get on stage.
German Günther Bauer blends in "Flamenco - people" the theatre of some performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flamenco Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of conveying on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a clean personality and character.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars."
With the festival "Song Popular des Mines", Bauer began a long trip in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a photo-plated camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, remind the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not dance or singing in itself, but the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic has been the constant of this work presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
The flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has transformed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exposed to the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a longer or longer moment.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that you sometimes don't know or that leave you just a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located on the 20th Street of the Mata (the road parallel to the people of Hercules) which will be opened until 16 October.
