A Sevillan dancer will pay tribute to a also Sevillan dancer.
Carmen Tortola Valencia, daughter of a Catalan father (Florenç Tortola Ferrer) and a Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district and who at the age of three will live in London with her family.
She was a free dance dancer and an oriental dance specialist.
She had an exciting life, pioneer of women's liberation, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was Buddhist and vegetarian and argued for the abolition of the corset that prevented the free movement of women.
The life of this woman who marked the history of the dance in Europe of the two wars, fascinated Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and the latter suggested that I interpret the Sevillan Dancer Tortola Valencia and it seemed amazing to me."
According to the dancer, "we don't try to tell her life but to translate her way of thinking.
His dance titles made me think of flamenco.
So, "the butterfly dance" made me think of a Cuban popular dance and "the snake dance" to some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and they told me that my way of dancing was the same as hers," she says.
The performance was made thanks to two outstanding contributions: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing again Isabela in one of her performances, as he had done at "The Open Door"; and that of Professor Matilde Coral, who exceptionally well wanted to collaborate with her student.
"Matilde transforms Tortola into a mature character.
I am happy because she has agreed to play a role in my work and this honors me."
The performance was also performed thanks to the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres y Paco Arriaga, the popular song of Michel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi de Morón; the percussions of El Pájaro, as well as the rape of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of this kind of artists who were considered to be divas".
This work also tells, in some ways, the life of this woman who has exhibited herself in places so far away, especially at the time, as in India, the United States, or Russia, but also throughout Europe, since she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think it is these women who have enormous influence in their time and now nobody knows and highlights her work," says Bayón.
