Recidivists of alcohol on the steering wheel will have to install the 'alcohol' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for alcoholism to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the start of the vehicle in drinking condition, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last a year.
Its purpose is to reinstate the driver by offering him courses in road re-education.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the Directorate General for Road Safety and the Foundation Institute for the Safety of Car will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once intoxicated, resumes the car.
Alcohol will avoid this because it is a connected system on the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol rate is higher than the one allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 people each year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by regular means, but criminal reform requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as has been done in France.
