Talking in Sleep
Some kids talk during the night.
I do not refer to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who speak during their sleep.
The first time this happens may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It's a benign sleep alteration called sleepwalking.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadicly (once in life for example associated with a severe fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often related to other sleeping disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night uresis (bedding in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very severe fevers, stress situations or overexcitation.
It's a little studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with screams, cries, long speeches ...
In the event that sleepoloquia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes much anxiety and to get an explanation of this problem.
We said that this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleeping alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With very nervous and relaxing children, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm indoors.
This will enable the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreams appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what it says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question it for information.
You won't get anything, because he's asleep, he's not aware to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
