Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest plan of economic rescue since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been taking place in Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both Congress Chambers.
It includes: better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, as well as a right to look at wages paid to the executives of the assisted companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the current crisis on Wall Street," the democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the American daily life will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had made a start in the last few hours out of fear of the effect that would cause a new failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline for opening the markets this morning was agreed.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their discontent that they were forced to reach that end.
Democrat Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, in particular that to allow owners to keep their homes and that on the salary of government-backed business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked about another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The main lines I have read [show] that it is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unspoiled debts of the American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of mortgage at risk (subprimary) credits before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze on liquidity and on the imbalance of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican elites who had made the first draft of the agreement capitulate last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been lifted since Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are assured only by the government rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone at Congress, a provision was also added that if the government was to take five years' losses with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its placement.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion to which additional 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion more should be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will be able to obtain participations in assisted companies that will be worth dividends in case of profit and that it will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans involved in this plan, as well as to set limits on pay and departure allowances paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plans will have the green light.
In fact, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
"Of course, Washington does not hear you," stated Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Commission to his electors.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one to take advantage of taxpayers."
An entertainer of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of the sceptics", the Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but arrives at the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic teachers, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to tell us: Congress is asked not to hurry and carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had renounced its full-fledged competitor since it had lost EUR 2 billion (US 2.9 billion) in the risk real estate loan crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In return, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
It is precisely something that savings and households now appreciate that times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be attempting to nationalize another bank under the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all ongoing loans from Bradford and Bringley, including more than US$ 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it was the one who would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
