What could possibly make Zuschlag &amp; Company in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the current criminal procedure will begin, against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, which has resulted in particularly significant damage.
According to the public prosecutor's office, money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and municipalities, approximately HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand in the caisses of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the authorities responsible for the investigation, was to pay the money of the grants obtained by issuing invoices of fees, after which no actual benefit was provided and thus, the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they were providing invoice books in the Józsefváros market, while they made the seals in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were to appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's deposition, he had to find pensions and restaurants.
For personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the model on which they made the other invoices they were going to introduce, inter alia, with the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as with the City of Capital for access to grants.
The majority of invoices were created by István Lados and by his accomplice András . .ri, who, according to our information, was primarily concerned with drafting the files necessary for obtaining the grants.
In a search circuit, one of Lados' choice was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlags in 2003, this place has ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice established on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will subsequently bear the name of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of forms and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
The issuers of invoices to the overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, which also belonged to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither Jobb Jövőert's name nor the name of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
