The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in Neurology and Economics at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this kind of competition, such as an eBay auction sale, and that is why they prefer to even pay too high a price.
These researches have tried to develop a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using sales at experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a sale at play auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging process (RMF), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale to auctions whose essential element is the oversale of a third party, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
That is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, economic members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overcrowded against a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
In another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the part, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is, in fact, that the emphasis was placed on victory in one side, while in the other, on failure.
By thus proving the assumption of neurologists, the members of the player team "against failure" were willing to take higher steps than those performed by the control group and the "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena found during auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade at risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped eliminate the contradiction between the two theories, leading to a third explanation now." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
One hundred miles are estimated to be the patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow treatment, which is because the patients often do not know they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against viruses A and B is nevertheless recommended. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by a general poor condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowness, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogen suddenly destroys the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
Pollution is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult its physician treating from the observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 by the organizations representing patients in the four corners of the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Do those who grow up in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that said researchers at Oxford University had an interesting experience by analyzing how much belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this experience for the least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
The results show that Catholic believers have been able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brains responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience takes place as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and disseminating electrochocs is set on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with hermine painted by Leonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
Researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a sort of state of faith among believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, they received 20 electrochocs in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general one.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safely", as someone we "care for" and they "quieted down, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% pain less than when looking at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided we find the appropriate picture.
"We should find an image in which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, indeed change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if one Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same size were shown to believers?
Would the view of a Virgin Mary of the highest quality lead to better results?
