The smart car imitates the bourdon flight
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle if it was not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bourdonant bees gave the strategic idea of starting Nissan's engineers to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotized system, type BR23C, which he has equipped with bee qualities, with the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own space, of oval shape, which actually resembles much of our safe protection shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and the technological public relations of the brand.
The bee's face-eye plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of face-to-face eye, engineers addressed the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Contrary to any existing system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
"If this was not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the Director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place at a glance.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot could be used.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is larger, which makes their life longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only treat a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a giga-byte capacity, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into serial cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
