Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - communicates to the Central Bureau of Statistics of Hungary.
Industrial export prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared with those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry only increased by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and shoe manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
A deflation resulted in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, steam and water, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a comparison of 12 months, taking into account the domestic sales of processing sectors, it is the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the manufacturing sector of metallurgical products, there was an increase in prices by 13.2 per cent, while in the important field of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase increased between 0.6% and 9.1%.
In the entire processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent during the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation in August were the investment profit-initiating sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for subsequent processing did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while in the profit-initiating sectors a 1.4 per cent decrease was observed.
The export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared with August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
