Mp3 player pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Cssseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - let us read in the note that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data, it is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in view of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels called on the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"The scientists-conclude the EU-executive confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European security standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but the concern increases as to hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reduction of levels and length of noise exposure.
The Scientific Committee Ue notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, are above the current limits on the maximum noise level agreed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions during prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at about 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
