Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market is not aware of the crisis
According to Sunia's last survey, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 euros in Florence, 650 euros in Naples, 600 euros in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding the whole categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high global costs that families of origin must support - explained the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand of students has distorted the market so that a process of generalized increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a number of violations: free-type contracts, not registered, no rent limit, sub-locations.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes approximately 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Black Band area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room approximately 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), approximately 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a double bed.
slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you move away to the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a simple one in the Predestina, Centocella or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, you must count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extra-Community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested by foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Adieu old cinema Paradiso, the cities eliminate historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favour of multiplexes.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore well illustrates what is happening in the large Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the large multi-sales, and the death of consumption of mono rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems to us to be inescapable and unquestionable; in addition, it has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and are charged with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of road and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, which offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and who told the poetry of a province hall, and nostalgia in a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the rooms of the main cities that paid the costs mainly: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilie Romaine is headed by 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirming that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, as it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multialle cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally" said Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should nevertheless guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a living room in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of credit for traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between €16 million and €18 million per year is needed.
We note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of these types in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono rooms of historic and peripheral centers.
The proposed regulations include measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and parking.
"It is an initiative that pleases" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that in order to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" to which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn from the other side to not see the black panels through the dust.
