When energy comes from waves, the big ones are now launching.
This is a stocked deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now major global energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossus like Chevron have set their eyes, and now they're trying to get their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When oil prices dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now the ecological authorities and the new increase in oil give rise to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 estimated that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by offshore mining systems.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colosses to the attack.
The first marine energy company was the Energysis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, we would have said a true revolutionary step.
At two years of this, more and more candidates among those companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy focus on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," said the spokesperson of a company associated with the American oil colossus, the Wall Street Journal, and it assesses opportunities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit deliberated by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if we consider that just in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. From New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which travel the route of energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested so far, although their details are not known, indicate, according to observers, an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about technology at its beginning, on the other hand, the fact that marine energy does not dispel fear of environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create a major problem in the ecosystem.
To produce large-scale energy, however, technology needs to be used with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The push of the waves, which moves the mud upwards and downwards, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floaters.
The pressure turns a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through cables under the sea.
For now, we have four systems of this kind in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the contrary, already produces energy for a commercial centre and a parking space using six marine turbines from the East River of New York.
The movement of water at tides, rotates the turbine blades, creating a rotating movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced to have a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electrical Energy, now deserves the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely about the energy of tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested $7 million and half dollars in 2008 and plan investments up to 35 million in 2009.
